close_reason: "Implemented and verified in the atomic work-selection, dependency-integrity, recovery, alias, and telemetry bundle."
body: "## Evidence (2026-07-07)\nWith four items legitimately in_progress by codex-agent (pm-w89s/pm-x6jf/pm-cbwg under epic pm-usfg, all updated today), pm next invoked by a different caller recommends pm-w89s with reasons including 'in progress — resume to finish' and assignee: codex-agent in the same payload. The envelope tells one agent to resume another agent's active work.\n\n## Why it matters\nClaim-level protection exists (pm-8t5x conflict-on-held, PR#430 ownership semantics) but the recommendation layer routes agents INTO those conflicts: N agents all get told to resume the same foreign WIP, then N-1 bounce at claim time (the exact thundering-herd pm-114v describes) or, worse, mutate without claiming since claims are advisory. At the pm-9rxu scale story (thousands of concurrent agents) recommendation-side ownership awareness is load-bearing, not polish.\n\n## Fix sketch\nResolve caller identity from the same author-resolution chain mutations use (PM_AUTHOR/config author_default; pm-cpja is making this ergonomic). If the recommended candidate has an assignee different from the caller: skip to the next candidate by default, and annotate the skipped one under a new held_by_others section (id + assignee only) so visibility is preserved without a resume instruction. Unassigned or self-assigned WIP keeps today's resume behavior. When caller identity is unresolvable, keep current behavior but replace the reason with 'in progress — assigned to <agent>; coordinate before resuming'. SDK-first: implement in the shared next-ranking primitive so CLI/MCP/SDK agree; relates to pm-114v (claim --next should reuse the same caller-aware ranking)."
